WEBVTT

00:01.585 --> 00:04.630
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.630 --> 00:11.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.891 --> 00:17.476
<i>‐ My name is James Maize.</i>

00:17.476 --> 00:20.020
<i>One of the things I really love</i>
<i>about making blades is,</i>

00:20.020 --> 00:21.480
it's not real common.

00:21.480 --> 00:23.649
<i>I do believe I'm a craftsman.</i>

00:23.649 --> 00:26.818
I really take pride
in what I do,

00:26.818 --> 00:29.988
and I'm super excited
about this competition.

00:29.988 --> 00:31.782
Let's bring it on.

00:31.782 --> 00:33.325
<i>‐ My name's Peter Hill.</i>

00:33.325 --> 00:36.703
One Christmas my wife bought me
a book on bladesmithing.

00:36.703 --> 00:39.790
<i>Now I look at everything</i>
<i>as either a knife part</i>

00:39.790 --> 00:42.501
<i>or something</i>
<i>I could make a knife into.</i>

00:42.501 --> 00:46.338
It's a sickness,
my wife would say, a passion.

00:46.338 --> 00:47.714
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:47.714 --> 00:50.551
<i>‐ My name's Kodee Artis.</i>
<i>I am from Iyanbito, New Mexico.</i>

00:50.551 --> 00:52.010
<i>Growing up Navajo,</i>

00:52.010 --> 00:54.638
bladesmithing and crafting
is in my blood,

00:54.638 --> 00:56.556
<i>because, you know,</i>
<i>on the reservation,</i>

00:56.556 --> 00:59.476
we don't have a lot
of technological advances.

00:59.476 --> 01:02.980
<i>We really know how to adapt</i>
<i>to our surroundings</i>

01:02.980 --> 01:05.357
<i>and what's given to us.</i>

01:05.357 --> 01:07.109
<i>‐ My name is Dr. Everett Stone.</i>

01:07.109 --> 01:08.902
I'm a research
assistant professor

01:08.902 --> 01:10.696
at the University of Texas,

01:10.696 --> 01:13.865
<i>where I develop</i>
<i>novel cancer drugs.</i>

01:13.865 --> 01:17.035
<i>I went to horseshoeing school</i>
<i>at age 16,</i>

01:17.035 --> 01:19.288
<i>and that introduced me</i>
<i>to forging.</i>

01:19.288 --> 01:20.747
<i>I would say "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>has been a very positive</i>

01:20.747 --> 01:23.458
influence on my knife making.

01:23.458 --> 01:25.544
<i>I love that it elevates</i>

01:25.544 --> 01:28.547
the awareness
of all the details

01:28.547 --> 01:30.799
that need to go into
making a really nice knife.

01:30.799 --> 01:32.092
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:32.092 --> 01:34.886
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:34.886 --> 01:36.763
You are here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:36.763 --> 01:38.432
of edged weapon‐making
competition

01:38.432 --> 01:39.933
like none other on the planet

01:39.933 --> 01:41.768
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:41.768 --> 01:43.603
who will tell us which of you
is our next

01:43.603 --> 01:45.063
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:45.063 --> 01:47.691
walking out of this place
with $10,000.

01:47.691 --> 01:50.569
Let's go ahead and meet
that panel of experts now.

01:50.569 --> 01:53.613
Up first, ABS Mastersmith
J. Neilson,

01:53.613 --> 01:56.742
historic weapons re‐creation
specialist David Baker,

01:56.742 --> 02:01.621
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

02:01.621 --> 02:05.000
All right, gentlemen, in this
first round of competition

02:05.000 --> 02:08.587
you'll have to harvest
the steel from this.

02:08.587 --> 02:09.671
Are you ready
to see what it is?

02:09.671 --> 02:17.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:17.304 --> 02:19.348
‐ Yes.

02:19.348 --> 02:21.391
‐ Gentlemen, you'll have
to harvest the steel

02:21.391 --> 02:23.268
that you need
to create signature blades

02:23.268 --> 02:26.938
in your signature style
from this go‐kart.

02:26.938 --> 02:30.484
<i>‐ Yeah. That'll be fun</i>
<i>to salvage something off of,</i>

02:30.484 --> 02:32.277
the springs, the axle.

02:32.277 --> 02:34.613
‐ One other thing.
You must source everything

02:34.613 --> 02:36.573
that you need
to make your blade

02:36.573 --> 02:39.951
from a single tire
on this go‐kart.

02:39.951 --> 02:42.621
I'm gonna let that one sink in.

02:42.621 --> 02:45.499
That's for your blade
and handle material.

02:45.499 --> 02:48.043
You will not have
any additional handle material.

02:48.043 --> 02:51.254
<i>‐ I'm thinking, "Okay, it has</i>
<i>some leaf springs in the front.</i>

02:51.254 --> 02:52.798
<i>That's usable."</i>

02:52.798 --> 02:57.135
<i>Then he comes up with,</i>
<i>"You can only use the wheels."</i>

02:57.135 --> 02:58.720
♪ Bum‐bum‐bum ♪

02:58.720 --> 03:01.139
<i>That kinda blew my bubble.</i>

03:01.139 --> 03:03.308
‐ Now, if you make it to the
second round of competition,

03:03.308 --> 03:04.685
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

03:04.685 --> 03:07.187
so that we can test them
for strength and durability

03:07.187 --> 03:11.358
in an axle smash and for
edge retention in a rope slice.

03:11.358 --> 03:13.777
You'll have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:13.777 --> 03:15.153
At the end of this round,

03:15.153 --> 03:17.197
after the judges
have inspected your work,

03:17.197 --> 03:19.533
one of you will be asked
to surrender your blade

03:19.533 --> 03:20.951
and leave The Forge.

03:20.951 --> 03:24.746
Good luck, gentlemen.
Your three hours starts now.

03:24.746 --> 03:28.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:28.834 --> 03:33.004
These guys have three hours
to rip the wheels off of this

03:33.004 --> 03:36.550
go‐kart and try to make
a knife out of it.

03:36.550 --> 03:39.928
It's a‐hammerin'
on these tires.

03:39.928 --> 03:42.389
‐ We've got high‐carbon steel
lug nuts...

03:42.389 --> 03:44.015
‐ Okay.
‐ That they're gonna pop off

03:44.015 --> 03:46.393
and forge weld them together
to make enough steel.

03:46.393 --> 03:48.562
‐ But James has gone over
to the pantry,

03:48.562 --> 03:50.897
and he's grabbed a canister.

03:50.897 --> 03:52.065
‐ We almost never get somebody

03:52.065 --> 03:54.860
who voluntarily
makes a canister.

03:54.860 --> 03:57.612
<i>‐ The reason why I have</i>
<i>a canister in mind is,</i>

03:57.612 --> 04:01.074
<i>I will cut the lug nuts up</i>
<i>so that they'll have a shape,</i>

04:01.074 --> 04:05.245
<i>and it'll give me</i>
<i>a good design in my billet.</i>

04:05.245 --> 04:06.663
‐ A can's not a bad idea.

04:06.663 --> 04:08.206
You've got to forge weld
anyway.

04:08.206 --> 04:10.167
‐ Drawback is
he used White Out,

04:10.167 --> 04:11.543
so he's gonna have to take

04:11.543 --> 04:15.005
that probably 20 to 30 minutes
to knock that can off.

04:15.005 --> 04:16.381
‐ Right.

04:16.381 --> 04:17.757
‐ And then are you done
with that over there?

04:17.757 --> 04:19.134
‐ Take that one.
‐ Okay.

04:19.134 --> 04:20.927
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:20.927 --> 04:23.180
<i>‐ I'm hitting these lug nuts</i>
<i>as hard as I can.</i>

04:23.180 --> 04:25.932
‐ All right,
Kodee's got one off.

04:25.932 --> 04:28.018
<i>‐ I decide I need</i>
<i>three lug nuts.</i>

04:28.018 --> 04:30.395
That should be enough steel,
because if I stack them

04:30.395 --> 04:31.563
on top of each other,

04:31.563 --> 04:33.732
I can make them
into a longer billet.

04:33.732 --> 04:37.569
‐ So many of the challenges
involve material management.

04:37.569 --> 04:39.237
It's how much steel you harvest

04:39.237 --> 04:42.407
and start that forging with
that really counts.

04:42.407 --> 04:44.576
<i>‐ I want to be the first</i>
<i>Dine Navajo</i>

04:44.576 --> 04:47.120
"Forged in Fire" champion,
and I hope being here

04:47.120 --> 04:49.498
inspires other Navajos
to take up bladesmithing.

04:49.498 --> 04:51.124
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:51.124 --> 04:53.418
‐ Don't know what I'm gonna
frickin' do here.

04:53.418 --> 04:54.628
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:54.628 --> 04:55.670
<i>For a long time</i>
<i>I've made knives</i>

04:55.670 --> 04:57.297
out of all kinds of junk.

04:57.297 --> 04:59.716
And I can certainly make
a knife out of some nuts.

04:59.716 --> 05:01.468
[laughs]

05:01.468 --> 05:04.095
<i>So I knock three</i>
<i>of these lug nuts off.</i>

05:04.095 --> 05:05.972
<i>I'm debating on some more.</i>

05:05.972 --> 05:07.557
Holy moly.

05:07.557 --> 05:10.101
I want to make sure
I have enough steel,

05:10.101 --> 05:12.437
but my arm's failing.

05:12.437 --> 05:13.980
‐ They're gonna be tired
of swinging the hammer

05:13.980 --> 05:15.649
before they even get to forge.

05:15.649 --> 05:18.401
<i>‐ So I knock two more off</i>
<i>and start heating them up.</i>

05:18.401 --> 05:19.736
Whew.

05:19.736 --> 05:24.324
This first round is gonna be
one hell of a challenge.

05:24.324 --> 05:27.786
‐ Looks like Everett's got four
of those lugs off.

05:27.786 --> 05:31.289
‐ I feel like I'm well‐suited
to the challenge.

05:31.289 --> 05:35.168
I spent a lot of time
making scrap Damascus

05:35.168 --> 05:37.295
and scrap this and scrap that.

05:37.295 --> 05:38.839
<i>Whether I can do this challenge</i>

05:38.839 --> 05:42.217
in three hours
is another question, of course.

05:42.217 --> 05:44.719
I get the four lug nuts
flattened down pretty nice.

05:44.719 --> 05:46.012
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:46.012 --> 05:48.723
I am welding up my four pieces.

05:48.723 --> 05:50.141
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:50.141 --> 05:52.853
‐ Uh‐oh. Everett welded
a C clamp to the billet.

05:52.853 --> 05:54.688
He's got to take care
of that quick.

05:54.688 --> 05:55.981
‐ [bleep].

05:55.981 --> 05:58.316
‐ So now I have to use
the angle grinder

05:58.316 --> 06:02.153
to cut the weld in order
to get that free,

06:02.153 --> 06:05.991
<i>so this cost me a lot of time.</i>

06:05.991 --> 06:08.743
‐ Bladesmiths,
60 minutes has elapsed.

06:08.743 --> 06:13.164
That leaves you two hours
remaining to finish your work.

06:13.164 --> 06:15.041
<i>‐ I'm gonna clean up these</i>
<i>billets,</i>

06:15.041 --> 06:18.503
smash them up, draw them out,
and make a knife.

06:18.503 --> 06:21.673
If you don't get the scale off,
it's not gonna bond.

06:21.673 --> 06:25.218
<i>Preparation is key</i>
<i>to the whole operation</i>

06:25.218 --> 06:27.971
of getting steel billets
stuck together.

06:27.971 --> 06:29.180
Whew.

06:29.180 --> 06:30.765
<i>‐ So we're an hour into it,</i>

06:30.765 --> 06:33.518
<i>and Peter's just welding</i>
<i>his stack up.</i>

06:33.518 --> 06:35.103
He spent an hour‐‐
an hour cleaning up.

06:35.103 --> 06:37.230
‐ It will be real material.

06:37.230 --> 06:39.816
‐ He's not in a hurry at all,

06:39.816 --> 06:42.861
and that's worrisome
in a timed competition.

06:42.861 --> 06:44.362
<i>‐ I'm gonna move</i>
<i>at my own pace.</i>

06:44.362 --> 06:45.906
<i>It's my way or the highway.</i>

06:45.906 --> 06:47.616
My wife's gonna love that one.

06:47.616 --> 06:49.034
[laughs]

06:49.034 --> 06:50.243
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:50.243 --> 06:52.954
‐ Looking at James,
that's a big canister.

06:52.954 --> 06:54.873
‐ He could have cut
that canister in half.

06:54.873 --> 06:57.292
It's gonna take so much longer
to get to the right temperature

06:57.292 --> 07:00.545
to forge weld it
and forge a blade out of it.

07:00.545 --> 07:04.257
‐ This is where everything
really sucks doing a canister.

07:04.257 --> 07:05.508
You put it in the forge,

07:05.508 --> 07:07.177
and you've got to
leave it alone.

07:07.177 --> 07:08.845
There's nothing I can do.

07:08.845 --> 07:11.723
<i>Watching the other bladesmiths</i>
<i>forge weld their billets,</i>

07:11.723 --> 07:12.891
<i>start drawing out blades,</i>

07:12.891 --> 07:15.769
<i>and I'm watching</i>
<i>my can heat‐soak.</i>

07:15.769 --> 07:18.104
<i>If I let this bother me</i>
<i>too much,</i>

07:18.104 --> 07:20.774
it takes my focus away
from the endgame.

07:20.774 --> 07:22.317
That's getting hot.

07:22.317 --> 07:24.027
So I know I've got a big
mountain ahead of me to climb,

07:24.027 --> 07:25.862
but I'm gonna get over it.

07:28.740 --> 07:30.450
‐ Everett did just
what I was hoping.

07:30.450 --> 07:34.621
He only flattened those pieces
out to about maybe 4 inches

07:34.621 --> 07:36.414
and then ground them
and stacked them up,

07:36.414 --> 07:38.708
so he had less surface area
to worry about forge welding.

07:38.708 --> 07:42.420
‐ He's really showing a lot
of technical skill here.

07:42.420 --> 07:44.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:44.255 --> 07:46.257
<i>‐ I would say that my life</i>
<i>has been lived</i>

07:46.257 --> 07:47.967
<i>outside of a box.</i>

07:47.967 --> 07:49.803
Ferrier's craft is pretty much

07:49.803 --> 07:52.597
a nonstop outside‐the‐box
type of thing,

07:52.597 --> 07:56.142
and my current job of designing
and testing cancer therapies,

07:56.142 --> 07:58.103
I mean,
that is all outside the box

07:58.103 --> 08:00.355
and‐‐as far as thinking.
This is fun.

08:00.355 --> 08:02.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.065 --> 08:04.442
‐ Kodee's got those
three pieces of steel,

08:04.442 --> 08:08.446
and right now he looks
a little short on steel.

08:08.446 --> 08:10.782
‐ My blade is getting too thin.

08:10.782 --> 08:13.118
<i>Thin blades are not always bad,</i>

08:13.118 --> 08:17.247
but this is not
a filet challenge.

08:17.247 --> 08:18.748
This blade has to be
for chopping

08:18.748 --> 08:21.084
and also able to slice.

08:21.084 --> 08:22.836
‐ When you starting to work
with a billet

08:22.836 --> 08:25.255
that's getting very thin,
it's gonna warp.

08:25.255 --> 08:27.298
‐ So that's the biggest‐‐

08:27.298 --> 08:28.633
there's five lug nuts
out there.

08:28.633 --> 08:31.010
There's time for Kodee
to virtually start over again.

08:31.010 --> 08:32.345
‐ Ahh.

08:32.345 --> 08:34.180
<i>So in another world,</i>
<i>I would actually go back</i>

08:34.180 --> 08:36.808
and grab another lug nut
and forge weld that

08:36.808 --> 08:39.185
<i>to make it a little big meatier</i>
<i>on the spine,</i>

08:39.185 --> 08:41.855
but I don't have enough time.

08:41.855 --> 08:43.398
I gotta keep moving forward.

08:43.398 --> 08:45.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:45.900 --> 08:47.402
‐ Son of a bitch.

08:47.402 --> 08:48.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:48.987 --> 08:51.698
So in the process
of taking the leap

08:51.698 --> 08:53.116
to make a canister weld,

08:53.116 --> 08:55.744
you know you've got to get
this can off.

08:55.744 --> 08:56.995
Mm.

08:56.995 --> 08:58.329
<i>And I beat my knuckles up.</i>

08:58.329 --> 09:03.084
I pinch my finger,
just one thing after another,

09:03.084 --> 09:06.046
but you gotta keep fighting.

09:06.046 --> 09:09.799
I finally get my billet out,
and I'm just in a zone.

09:09.799 --> 09:11.718
‐ James still has more steel
than he needs,

09:11.718 --> 09:13.803
but what he's got looks good.

09:13.803 --> 09:16.056
‐ I'm way behind the game.

09:16.056 --> 09:18.349
‐ Bladesmiths,
two hours has elapsed.

09:18.349 --> 09:21.019
You have just
60 minutes remaining.

09:21.019 --> 09:22.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:22.395 --> 09:26.232
‐ I'm making some kind of
hacker, slasher, chopper,

09:26.232 --> 09:29.319
<i>bolo‐y‐‐we'll call</i>
<i>it the Dune Buggy Special.</i>

09:29.319 --> 09:30.862
[laughs]

09:30.862 --> 09:31.863
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:31.863 --> 09:33.907
<i>J. Neilson is gonna be beating</i>

09:33.907 --> 09:35.784
the living hell
out of something with this,

09:35.784 --> 09:38.620
so I have a fairly
thick spine throughout,

09:38.620 --> 09:40.580
<i>a bit of a distal taper.</i>

09:40.580 --> 09:43.124
<i>That should help hold up</i>
<i>from breaking,</i>

09:43.124 --> 09:45.543
and it won't ding
under pressure.

09:45.543 --> 09:48.088
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:48.088 --> 09:50.548
‐ Peter's got a great shape
on that knife.

09:50.548 --> 09:54.886
‐ I get my blade to shape
and decide to drill some holes.

09:54.886 --> 09:58.765
I'm drilling now
just to set up for round two.

09:58.765 --> 10:01.935
It's a lot easier than after
you heat‐treat it.

10:01.935 --> 10:03.853
Whoo‐whee.

10:03.853 --> 10:06.606
‐ 30 minutes remaining
in the round.

10:06.606 --> 10:08.233
Kodee's got a very thin blade.

10:08.233 --> 10:10.276
‐ Yeah, I think Kodee's
best bet right now,

10:10.276 --> 10:12.320
if he's gonna stick with that
piece of steel,

10:12.320 --> 10:14.155
flatten it, quench it,
and go to the grinder

10:14.155 --> 10:15.740
and clean it up
the best you can.

10:15.740 --> 10:19.869
<i>‐ Time is ticking down,</i>
<i>and I need to quench</i>

10:19.869 --> 10:22.080
so I can fix any warps
or cracks.

10:22.080 --> 10:23.832
‐ Here we go. Here we go.
Look at that.

10:23.832 --> 10:25.291
Kodee's quenched his blade.

10:25.291 --> 10:26.584
He's got a jig set up.

10:26.584 --> 10:29.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:29.129 --> 10:31.131
<i>‐ The warp in my blade</i>
<i>is too severe,</i>

10:31.131 --> 10:32.841
so I try to straighten it out.

10:32.841 --> 10:34.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:34.634 --> 10:37.345
‐ Only got a couple seconds
here to get that dialed in.

10:37.345 --> 10:41.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:41.015 --> 10:42.809
<i>‐ I take my knife out</i>
<i>of the straightening jig,</i>

10:42.809 --> 10:44.769
and the warp's still there.

10:44.769 --> 10:46.104
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:46.104 --> 10:49.315
I'm hoping that I can flex
the warp out of it.

10:49.315 --> 10:53.444
‐ Man, Kodee's flexing the hell
out of that blade.

10:53.444 --> 10:58.158
‐ Oh, don't do that.

10:58.158 --> 10:59.117
[blade clangs]

10:59.117 --> 11:01.035
‐ Oh!
‐ Oh, man.

11:01.035 --> 11:02.078
‐ [bleep].

11:02.078 --> 11:03.746
‐ With 24 minutes
left on the clock,

11:03.746 --> 11:05.707
Kodee just snapped his blade.

11:05.707 --> 11:07.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:07.167 --> 11:08.835
<i>‐ Oh, my God.</i>
<i>I'm angry with myself,</i>

11:08.835 --> 11:11.880
but also, like,
just‐‐I'm so emotional.

11:11.880 --> 11:13.506
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:13.506 --> 11:15.675
<i>But I'm Navajo.</i>

11:15.675 --> 11:17.552
We're resilient.

11:17.552 --> 11:19.637
<i>I don't have enough time</i>
<i>to start another blade,</i>

11:19.637 --> 11:21.055
<i>so I just keep going.</i>

11:21.055 --> 11:23.975
I can possibly forge weld it
back together.

11:23.975 --> 11:25.602
Did he flap the two ends over?

11:25.602 --> 11:28.354
‐ Yeah, he's ground it
so they can overlap each other,

11:28.354 --> 11:30.023
tack welded them on there.

11:30.023 --> 11:31.774
He's gonna try and forge weld
those two pieces back together.

11:31.774 --> 11:33.610
‐ Okay, that's commendable.

11:33.610 --> 11:36.196
I would love to see
this pay off.

11:36.196 --> 11:37.822
<i>‐ I don't know what this is</i>
<i>gonna turn out as,</i>

11:37.822 --> 11:39.991
but let's‐‐let's keep
pressing forward.

11:39.991 --> 11:43.536
‐ This is panic mode for Kodee.

11:43.536 --> 11:45.038
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:45.038 --> 11:49.209
<i>James caught back up,</i>
<i>and it looks pretty good.</i>

11:49.209 --> 11:52.086
‐ I'm fatigued.
My forearms are cramping up,

11:52.086 --> 11:54.047
<i>but I'm gonna finish</i>
<i>this knife.</i>

11:54.047 --> 11:57.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:57.383 --> 12:00.136
And then I see a big warp.

12:00.136 --> 12:01.554
I gotta heat it up,
straighten it,

12:01.554 --> 12:03.181
and re‐quench it.

12:03.181 --> 12:06.392
Put it back in my quench oil...

12:06.392 --> 12:07.518
Damn it.

12:07.518 --> 12:09.479
<i>And it warps again.</i>

12:09.479 --> 12:12.941
Quenching a third time
at this point is not an option.

12:12.941 --> 12:14.651
The time is just ticking by.

12:14.651 --> 12:17.570
I gotta go with it.

12:17.570 --> 12:18.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:18.905 --> 12:20.865
<i>‐ Decide I want to do</i>
<i>a edge quench,</i>

12:20.865 --> 12:23.243
because I want the back
of the blade soft,

12:23.243 --> 12:25.078
and I want the edge hard.

12:25.078 --> 12:26.704
Augh.

12:26.704 --> 12:30.208
‐ Peter messing with the torch
with 16 minutes left.

12:30.208 --> 12:31.292
‐ Ay‐yi‐yi.

12:31.292 --> 12:32.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:32.794 --> 12:35.129
<i>‐ If I keep spinning my wheels</i>
<i>with this edge quench,</i>

12:35.129 --> 12:37.423
I'm not gonna be in round two.

12:37.423 --> 12:41.469
I decide to scrap it
and just do a full hardening.

12:41.469 --> 12:43.805
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:43.805 --> 12:46.474
I feel I had a good quench,

12:46.474 --> 12:49.102
but we'll find out
when J. smashes it.

12:49.102 --> 12:50.144
[laughs]

12:50.144 --> 12:53.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:53.147 --> 12:54.107
<i>‐ I look at the forge welds,</i>

12:54.107 --> 12:55.608
and I'm thinking
it's pretty good.

12:55.608 --> 12:58.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:58.236 --> 12:59.612
‐ All right, Kodee,

12:59.612 --> 13:02.073
he is in the quench
a second time around.

13:02.073 --> 13:04.784
‐ If Kodee's weld
didn't set completely,

13:04.784 --> 13:07.078
it's gonna be fractured
at that joint.

13:07.078 --> 13:08.621
<i>‐ It still has a warp to it.</i>

13:08.621 --> 13:10.248
Augh.

13:10.248 --> 13:12.292
And this time, I'm thinking
that it's hot enough

13:12.292 --> 13:14.669
that I can somehow
flex the warp out of it.

13:14.669 --> 13:16.671
‐ Don't flex it. Don't flex it.

13:16.671 --> 13:18.006
<i>‐ I'm trying to be</i>
<i>super gentle.</i>

13:18.006 --> 13:24.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:24.512 --> 13:26.639
‐ Oh, not again.
‐ Oh, man.

13:26.639 --> 13:29.851
‐ No.
‐ Oh, my God.

13:29.851 --> 13:31.644
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths.

13:31.644 --> 13:35.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:35.565 --> 13:38.401
‐ I'm frustrated, because
I've let myself down, you know?

13:38.401 --> 13:39.694
And‐‐ugh.

13:39.694 --> 13:40.945
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:40.945 --> 13:42.655
<i>But I've got to finish strong.</i>

13:42.655 --> 13:44.032
The Navajos don't quit.

13:44.032 --> 13:45.575
Welder.

13:45.575 --> 13:47.994
‐ Kodee's not giving up,
'cause you never know

13:47.994 --> 13:49.787
what's happening
with your other competitors.

13:49.787 --> 13:53.666
‐ Exactly.
‐ Three, two, one.

13:53.666 --> 13:55.126
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

13:55.126 --> 13:57.712
Drop your tools.
Hanner's blade is snapped.

13:57.712 --> 13:59.672
‐ Oh
‐ Oh, my God.

13:59.672 --> 14:03.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:03.843 --> 14:06.054
<i>‐ I feel like I'm ready</i>
<i>for the quench.</i>

14:06.054 --> 14:07.722
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:07.722 --> 14:11.392
‐ And we've got a quench
out of Everett.

14:11.392 --> 14:13.686
<i>‐ I pull it out, and I have</i>
<i>a large warp in there,</i>

14:13.686 --> 14:15.855
which is very irritating.

14:15.855 --> 14:17.607
<i>My thought process is,</i>

14:17.607 --> 14:20.026
<i>"Well, let me grind</i>
<i>a little bit out of this</i>

14:20.026 --> 14:23.154
"and at least get
some of the profile down,

14:23.154 --> 14:25.531
<i>"and if I move on</i>
<i>to round two,</i>

14:25.531 --> 14:29.494
I have a very good chance
of fixing this warp there."

14:29.494 --> 14:32.663
‐ Five, four, three,

14:32.663 --> 14:35.291
two, one,
bladesmiths,

14:35.291 --> 14:37.168
shut down your machines.
Drop your tools.

14:37.168 --> 14:40.922
This first round
of competition is over.

14:40.922 --> 14:43.549
‐ Whoo.
‐ Whoo!

14:43.549 --> 14:47.261
<i>This challenge was by far</i>
<i>the toughest challenge</i>

14:47.261 --> 14:50.098
<i>that I've had</i>
<i>in my bladesmithing career.</i>

14:50.098 --> 14:53.434
Taking something from nothing
in three hours,

14:53.434 --> 14:56.187
<i>turning it into what we</i>
<i>turned into</i>

14:56.187 --> 15:00.108
says something
about what we're doing.

15:00.108 --> 15:02.068
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
in this first go‐round

15:02.068 --> 15:04.779
we asked you guys to pull
the wheels off this go‐kart

15:04.779 --> 15:06.864
to make signature blades
in your signature style.

15:06.864 --> 15:09.075
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

15:09.075 --> 15:11.744
at what you've done
with your time.

15:11.744 --> 15:12.870
James, you're up first.

15:12.870 --> 15:14.789
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:14.789 --> 15:17.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:17.125 --> 15:19.460
<i>‐ James, that was a good idea</i>
<i>going with the canister.</i>

15:19.460 --> 15:21.129
<i>You pretty much</i>
<i>guaranteed yourself</i>

15:21.129 --> 15:22.797
that you were gonna have
more than enough steel.

15:22.797 --> 15:26.509
You do have quite a good warp
in here though.

15:26.509 --> 15:29.637
But you got a lot of meat
to fix that.

15:29.637 --> 15:31.305
Good job.

15:31.305 --> 15:32.431
‐ All right, Peter, you're up.

15:32.431 --> 15:34.267
Show the judges
what you've done.

15:34.267 --> 15:37.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:37.228 --> 15:38.771
<i>‐ I like it.</i>

15:38.771 --> 15:40.773
<i>You've got a lot of material</i>
<i>here still to work with.</i>

15:40.773 --> 15:43.192
I mean, the profile
already looks fantastic.

15:43.192 --> 15:46.070
I like that little drop to it,
so if you move forward,

15:46.070 --> 15:48.447
it's really refining this

15:48.447 --> 15:51.659
and turning it into
a real nice chopper. Good job.

15:51.659 --> 15:52.994
‐ All right, Doc Everett,
you're up.

15:52.994 --> 15:56.789
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:56.789 --> 15:58.166
<i>‐ All right, Everett,</i>

15:58.166 --> 15:59.542
<i>I like the design</i>
<i>you have here.</i>

15:59.542 --> 16:01.252
<i>It's designed for slashing.</i>

16:01.252 --> 16:03.171
You see it clears out,

16:03.171 --> 16:06.007
give a little weight
for chopping also.

16:06.007 --> 16:08.176
<i>You do have a warp,</i>
<i>but the good thing is,</i>

16:08.176 --> 16:09.844
there's enough metal
right here to correct that

16:09.844 --> 16:11.304
if you move forward
to the second round.

16:11.304 --> 16:12.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:12.847 --> 16:14.098
‐ All right, Kodee, you're up.

16:14.098 --> 16:16.142
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:16.142 --> 16:18.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:18.811 --> 16:20.938
<i>‐ Kodee, we got a few issues</i>
<i>with this.</i>

16:20.938 --> 16:23.024
I wish you had used more steel,

16:23.024 --> 16:25.193
but you were fighting
to stretch material out,

16:25.193 --> 16:28.321
and then it got so lean
that when you were trying

16:28.321 --> 16:31.199
to manipulate the blade,
snapped it.

16:31.199 --> 16:32.950
Smart thing you did, though,

16:32.950 --> 16:34.869
lapping those
and forge welding those.

16:34.869 --> 16:37.914
I gotta commend you
for not giving up.

16:37.914 --> 16:39.332
Good job.

16:39.332 --> 16:42.501
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

16:42.501 --> 16:44.128
They've made
their final decision.

16:44.128 --> 16:46.714
It's time for one of you smiths
to leave The Forge.

16:46.714 --> 16:49.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:49.383 --> 16:52.136
Kodee, your blade
didn't make the cut.

16:52.136 --> 16:53.971
Doug Marcaida's
gonna tell you why.

16:53.971 --> 16:57.642
‐ Kodee, this competition is
about coming into this arena

16:57.642 --> 17:00.353
and testing your skills
against a timed competition,

17:00.353 --> 17:03.272
so we just don't test
your metal but your mettle,

17:03.272 --> 17:05.816
and you made it through
with a blade to present,

17:05.816 --> 17:07.318
and that to me
makes it special,

17:07.318 --> 17:11.906
but that being said,
your blade has the most issues.

17:11.906 --> 17:14.075
‐ Kodee, please
surrender your blade.

17:14.075 --> 17:15.451
<i>‐ I'm definitely proud</i>
<i>of myself,</i>

17:15.451 --> 17:16.702
<i>because I kept</i>
<i>on pushing through,</i>

17:16.702 --> 17:18.246
<i>and I didn't give up.</i>

17:18.246 --> 17:20.915
<i>Like my pop always says,</i>
<i>life is not a spectator sport.</i>

17:20.915 --> 17:22.541
You gotta be in it.
You gotta take those risks,

17:22.541 --> 17:25.044
so I took a risk,
and I had a great time.

17:25.044 --> 17:28.172
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:28.172 --> 17:29.924
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

17:29.924 --> 17:32.426
You've made it to the second
round of this competition.

17:32.426 --> 17:34.804
Now you'll have two hours
to take those warped

17:34.804 --> 17:36.138
and tempered blades

17:36.138 --> 17:37.807
and turn them
into fully functional weapons

17:37.807 --> 17:39.141
by attaching handles to them.

17:39.141 --> 17:41.143
You'll source
the handle material

17:41.143 --> 17:43.145
from the tires of our go‐kart.

17:43.145 --> 17:44.855
At the end of this round,
your weapons

17:44.855 --> 17:48.025
will be tested for strength
and durability in an axle smash

17:48.025 --> 17:50.486
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

17:50.486 --> 17:52.572
I remind you that after
your blades have been tested,

17:52.572 --> 17:54.490
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

17:54.490 --> 17:55.908
and leave The Forge.

17:55.908 --> 17:58.953
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts now.

17:58.953 --> 18:00.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:00.496 --> 18:03.833
We've seen the tire
handle before.

18:03.833 --> 18:05.835
What do you think
of those materials?

18:05.835 --> 18:07.503
‐ Well, one thing,

18:07.503 --> 18:08.963
don't use the treads

18:08.963 --> 18:10.298
for your handle material
in terms

18:10.298 --> 18:12.049
of what's gonna be
touching your skin.

18:12.049 --> 18:14.635
The treads are not comfortable.

18:14.635 --> 18:17.597
<i>‐ The fact that we're putting</i>
<i>tires on as handles,</i>

18:17.597 --> 18:21.142
I'm thinking that that handle's
just gonna look like garbage,

18:21.142 --> 18:24.770
but hopefully it'll be
solid garbage.

18:24.770 --> 18:26.063
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:26.063 --> 18:29.275
‐ Everett is cutting sections
of tread.

18:29.275 --> 18:30.484
You think he's gonna stack it?
‐ Oh, yeah‐‐

18:30.484 --> 18:31.736
<i>‐ Got a hidden tang.</i>

18:31.736 --> 18:32.820
<i>‐ Yeah, he's got that</i>
<i>hidden tang,</i>

18:32.820 --> 18:34.155
<i>so he's pre‐set to stack.</i>

18:34.155 --> 18:36.741
<i>‐ I feel like the stack</i>
<i>is gonna be easier</i>

18:36.741 --> 18:40.036
than trying to get rubber tread

18:40.036 --> 18:42.663
to stick to a side of a knife.

18:42.663 --> 18:45.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:45.458 --> 18:48.127
‐ The first thing I'm gonna do
is cut out a piece of the tire

18:48.127 --> 18:51.339
and make sure it'll fit
to the sides of my handle.

18:51.339 --> 18:53.299
Eh, it might fit
freakin' work.

18:53.299 --> 18:56.510
Then it's a weight‐loss
program on my blade.

18:56.510 --> 18:59.472
‐ Peter's over here
on the 8‐inch contact wheel.

18:59.472 --> 19:01.682
‐ Hogging a lot
of material off.

19:01.682 --> 19:05.645
‐ I would have never considered
putting tires on a handle.

19:05.645 --> 19:07.730
<i>It's a pliable material.</i>

19:07.730 --> 19:10.650
It's not solid like
I'm used to working with.

19:10.650 --> 19:13.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:13.319 --> 19:15.780
‐ James looks like he's just
gonna slab some tread

19:15.780 --> 19:17.531
on the sides there.

19:17.531 --> 19:20.117
‐ I've got my tire
for the scales,

19:20.117 --> 19:22.203
<i>and I'm gonna take a pin</i>
<i>that is smaller</i>

19:22.203 --> 19:24.789
<i>than the size of my pin stock</i>

19:24.789 --> 19:28.000
and try to heat it up and burn
a hole through the rubber.

19:28.000 --> 19:30.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:30.753 --> 19:34.715
With the hole size being
slightly smaller than your pin,

19:34.715 --> 19:36.509
when you push your pin
through it,

19:36.509 --> 19:38.344
it's gonna hold it
a little bit tighter,

19:38.344 --> 19:41.180
<i>and it's gonna be</i>
<i>less apt to move.</i>

19:41.180 --> 19:45.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:45.559 --> 19:47.019
‐ All right.
‐ That's a good idea.

19:47.019 --> 19:49.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:49.522 --> 19:51.941
<i>‐ Using the tire,</i>
<i>you want to get it</i>

19:51.941 --> 19:53.984
<i>to squeeze up pretty tight,</i>

19:53.984 --> 19:57.863
because the rubber
will not be prone to twisting.

19:57.863 --> 19:59.824
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:59.824 --> 20:02.535
‐ The smart move; compress
that as much as you can.

20:02.535 --> 20:03.619
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:03.619 --> 20:05.579
<i>‐ And I picked up</i>
<i>a piece of brass</i>

20:05.579 --> 20:07.039
<i>that I want to use</i>
<i>for a butt cap,</i>

20:07.039 --> 20:09.083
<i>and it will be riveted in</i>
<i>on the hand.</i>

20:09.083 --> 20:12.378
It just can't go anywhere
that I‐‐that I know of.

20:12.378 --> 20:14.088
[laughs]

20:14.088 --> 20:15.589
It feels pretty solid.

20:15.589 --> 20:18.217
‐ Bladesmiths,
60 minutes has elapsed.

20:18.217 --> 20:21.262
‐ I've decided my buggy tires
aren't thick enough,

20:21.262 --> 20:23.264
<i>so I'm using some wooden liners</i>

20:23.264 --> 20:25.766
to make them
a little bit thicker.

20:25.766 --> 20:27.393
<i>I get two pins in, lined up.</i>

20:27.393 --> 20:28.728
All right, I'm going good,
and I'm thinking,

20:28.728 --> 20:30.062
"All right,
I'll slip the third pin in,"

20:30.062 --> 20:33.816
and I realize that my scales
are upside‐down.

20:33.816 --> 20:36.360
Oh, shoot.

20:36.360 --> 20:37.403
‐ Well, here's the thing.

20:37.403 --> 20:39.905
He's already epoxied
the scales,

20:39.905 --> 20:41.449
so he's gotta
do this very quickly.

20:41.449 --> 20:43.659
‐ Gotta get it done.
<i>‐ Yank them out of there,</i>

20:43.659 --> 20:46.787
turn it around before
the epoxy kicks.

20:46.787 --> 20:48.456
All right.

20:48.456 --> 20:50.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:50.040 --> 20:52.585
<i>‐ At this point, I decide</i>
<i>I'm going to attach my scale</i>

20:52.585 --> 20:54.086
<i>to one side of my blade.</i>

20:54.086 --> 20:57.798
So while the epoxy is drying,
I can work on the warp.

20:57.798 --> 21:00.676
<i>I think it's warm enough.</i>
<i>I grab the twisting wrench,</i>

21:00.676 --> 21:03.304
<i>and I start to put</i>
<i>pressure on it,</i>

21:03.304 --> 21:04.972
and this blade is not moving.

21:04.972 --> 21:06.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:06.474 --> 21:10.102
I realize I have a little bit
more of a warp in my blade

21:10.102 --> 21:12.313
than I initially thought.

21:12.313 --> 21:15.107
I give it a little bit more,
and it's not moving.

21:15.107 --> 21:18.986
‐ Oh, he's‐‐what are
you torquing on that blade for?

21:18.986 --> 21:20.780
‐ Forget the warp.

21:23.741 --> 21:26.118
‐ Oh, I knew it.

21:26.118 --> 21:27.787
‐ [bleep].

21:27.787 --> 21:29.830
‐ I knew that was gonna happen.
‐ I just saw that coming.

21:29.830 --> 21:32.249
<i>‐ I'm just numb. I'm so pissed.</i>

21:32.249 --> 21:35.294
Everything has just
gone out the window.

21:35.294 --> 21:37.630
<i>I remember Kodee</i>
<i>with his blade break,</i>

21:37.630 --> 21:41.300
and he just kept on pushing,
and I'm gonna be the same way.

21:41.300 --> 21:43.302
<i>I don't have access</i>
<i>to my forge,</i>

21:43.302 --> 21:45.304
so I have to weld it
back together.

21:45.304 --> 21:47.014
<i>I'm gonna do</i>
<i>my very best to recover</i>

21:47.014 --> 21:51.727
and produce a functional blade
in 38 minutes and 30 seconds.

21:51.727 --> 21:53.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:53.521 --> 21:55.815
<i>‐ A couple of these blades</i>
<i>have already broken</i>

21:55.815 --> 21:58.192
from attempting to fix warps.

21:58.192 --> 22:02.446
I am a little bit nervous
going into fixing my warp,

22:02.446 --> 22:05.699
<i>so I decide to go</i>
<i>with blue backing</i>

22:05.699 --> 22:08.702
<i>and mechanical straightening.</i>

22:08.702 --> 22:10.496
‐ He's got a jig worked out.
‐ I like that better.

22:10.496 --> 22:12.998
‐ Blue back it; let it relax.

22:12.998 --> 22:15.584
<i>‐ Take everything out,</i>
<i>and it is improved.</i>

22:15.584 --> 22:17.169
It's not perfect,

22:17.169 --> 22:20.714
but I figure this is better
than a broken blade.

22:20.714 --> 22:22.341
‐ 15 minutes.

22:22.341 --> 22:25.261
‐ Holy crap.
We're running out of time.

22:25.261 --> 22:26.887
I can't leave my handle
like this.

22:26.887 --> 22:28.180
It's like a big block.

22:28.180 --> 22:29.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:29.682 --> 22:30.808
<i>I'm gonna do whatever it takes</i>

22:30.808 --> 22:32.935
to get some kind of profile
shaped out.

22:32.935 --> 22:33.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:33.894 --> 22:35.437
<i>If I had more time,</i>

22:35.437 --> 22:38.732
I'd keep on grinding
to get a better finish on it,

22:38.732 --> 22:42.695
but I still need to put
a finishing edge on this knife.

22:42.695 --> 22:44.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.446 --> 22:46.407
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths.

22:46.407 --> 22:48.993
‐ I am so far behind my game.

22:48.993 --> 22:50.369
Come on.

22:50.369 --> 22:52.496
<i>I have to finish</i>
<i>shaping my handle,</i>

22:52.496 --> 22:56.375
and I also have to keep an eye
out for the little bit of warp

22:56.375 --> 22:58.836
<i>that might be in my blade</i>
<i>from welding it.</i>

22:58.836 --> 23:01.380
‐ He's not gentle
on that grind.

23:01.380 --> 23:02.840
‐ He might possibly just be
grinding his‐‐

23:02.840 --> 23:04.341
all his weld off right now.

23:04.341 --> 23:06.760
<i>‐ Well, at this point, I'm done</i>
<i>worrying about the clock.</i>

23:06.760 --> 23:09.096
<i>Now it's just work like hell</i>
<i>till they tell me</i>

23:09.096 --> 23:10.472
to put my blade on the anvil.

23:10.472 --> 23:12.558
‐ Five, four,

23:12.558 --> 23:15.936
three, two, one, bladesmiths,

23:15.936 --> 23:18.022
shut down your machines.
Drop your tools.

23:18.022 --> 23:22.234
This second round
of competition is over.

23:22.234 --> 23:24.612
<i>‐ I'm not happy with my blade.</i>

23:24.612 --> 23:26.155
I'm happy it's back together.

23:26.155 --> 23:30.242
I'm happy that it can be
considered a finished weapon,

23:30.242 --> 23:34.079
<i>but it's not</i>
<i>my quality work at all.</i>

23:34.079 --> 23:37.166
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test.

23:37.166 --> 23:39.752
Now, to continue
our vehicle theme,

23:39.752 --> 23:41.086
I'm gonna take your blades,

23:41.086 --> 23:43.923
and I'm gonna beat them
into this axle casing.

23:43.923 --> 23:45.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:45.299 --> 23:46.634
It's gonna test your heat treat

23:46.634 --> 23:48.928
and the overall construction
of your weapons.

23:48.928 --> 23:50.262
Now, I'm not concerned
about what your blades

23:50.262 --> 23:52.389
do to the axle.
I want the opposite.

23:52.389 --> 23:54.808
I want to see what the axle's
gonna do to your blades.

23:54.808 --> 23:56.435
James, you're up first.
You ready to go?

23:56.435 --> 23:58.520
‐ All right, let's get it over.
‐ Let's go.

23:58.520 --> 23:59.855
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:59.855 --> 24:02.608
<i>‐ Seeing what the challenge is,</i>
<i>expecting to have</i>

24:02.608 --> 24:05.986
<i>a little bitty go‐kart axle,</i>
<i>and I see a truck axle.</i>

24:08.155 --> 24:10.115
<i>‐ I'm freaking out.</i>

24:10.115 --> 24:11.867
I'm concerned with the weld
in my blade,

24:11.867 --> 24:13.994
and I'm thinking
I made a huge mistake

24:13.994 --> 24:16.455
<i>by trying to straighten it.</i>

24:16.455 --> 24:23.420
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:31.011 --> 24:32.054
‐ It didn't break.

24:32.054 --> 24:33.180
‐ It didn't break.

24:33.180 --> 24:34.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:34.640 --> 24:36.058
‐ Well, James,
we got a problem.

24:36.058 --> 24:38.310
Going back to weld that,

24:38.310 --> 24:40.938
a lot of the weld
got ground back off again,

24:40.938 --> 24:42.564
'cause if you look carefully
right here,

24:42.564 --> 24:43.941
it's just that little flap
of MIG weld

24:43.941 --> 24:46.318
that's holding it on one side,

24:46.318 --> 24:48.529
so it's obviously
a big problem.

24:48.529 --> 24:52.324
I commend you greatly
for putting the effort in

24:52.324 --> 24:53.867
and turning in a blade,

24:53.867 --> 24:56.662
but it didn't hold up.

24:56.662 --> 24:59.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:59.581 --> 25:02.167
‐ The beast from the east
came to play today,

25:02.167 --> 25:06.130
and, James, your blade suffered
a catastrophic blade failure

25:06.130 --> 25:07.881
on the third strike,

25:07.881 --> 25:10.175
but that doesn't mean that
you're out of this competition,

25:10.175 --> 25:12.928
because your competitors
still have to endure

25:12.928 --> 25:14.430
the challenge ahead of them.

25:14.430 --> 25:17.975
Gentlemen, if your blades
survive three strikes

25:17.975 --> 25:19.435
on this axle housing,

25:19.435 --> 25:21.478
you'll be moving forward.
Are you guys ready?

25:21.478 --> 25:22.563
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ J.

25:22.563 --> 25:28.027
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:28.027 --> 25:29.737
‐ Peter, how you feeling?

25:29.737 --> 25:33.824
‐ I'm betting on which one
is gonna be the longest after.

25:33.824 --> 25:36.910
[laughter]

25:36.910 --> 25:39.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:39.246 --> 25:40.414
<i>I'm feeling scared,</i>

25:40.414 --> 25:43.709
<i>and I'm feeling</i>
<i>a little nervous</i>

25:43.709 --> 25:45.085
what the outcome will be.

25:45.085 --> 25:52.051
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:55.721 --> 25:57.723
‐ Nice.
‐ [exhales]

25:57.723 --> 25:59.391
‐ That's a heart‐stopper.

25:59.391 --> 26:00.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:00.559 --> 26:01.852
‐ Congratulations, Peter.

26:01.852 --> 26:04.063
It survived three strikes.
Nicely done.

26:04.063 --> 26:07.149
‐ Thank you, sir.
‐ Ready, Everett?

26:07.149 --> 26:09.735
‐ I'm ready. Let's go out
to the old ball game.

26:09.735 --> 26:11.737
‐ Let's do it.

26:11.737 --> 26:13.363
<i>‐ This axle is a beast,</i>

26:13.363 --> 26:16.075
<i>and that edge could get</i>
<i>pretty damaged</i>

26:16.075 --> 26:18.285
from what J's doing to it.

26:18.285 --> 26:25.250
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:31.006 --> 26:34.593
‐ Good job.
‐ Good job.

26:34.593 --> 26:38.639
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:38.639 --> 26:42.476
‐ Peter, Everett, good job.
Your blades survived the test.

26:42.476 --> 26:45.646
James, you really did
fantastic work out there,

26:45.646 --> 26:47.981
but unfortunately, that snap

26:47.981 --> 26:49.983
in the second round
that you welded,

26:49.983 --> 26:53.237
it cost you here in testing,
and for that reason,

26:53.237 --> 26:56.657
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

26:56.657 --> 26:57.866
‐ I don't care who you are.

26:57.866 --> 26:59.993
This competition's
gonna be tough.

26:59.993 --> 27:01.912
No matter how much experience
you have,

27:01.912 --> 27:04.790
<i>some aspect of it</i>
<i>is gonna get you off your game,</i>

27:04.790 --> 27:07.292
<i>and you've gotta</i>
<i>recover from it.</i>

27:07.292 --> 27:08.627
<i>I'm proud of the fact</i>

27:08.627 --> 27:10.337
that through
everything that went wrong,

27:10.337 --> 27:11.964
I came through
all the adversity,

27:11.964 --> 27:13.966
<i>and I produced a weapon,</i>

27:13.966 --> 27:17.636
<i>and it's been</i>
<i>a wonderful experience.</i>

27:17.636 --> 27:19.012
‐ Peter, Everett,
congratulations.

27:19.012 --> 27:20.639
You fellas have made it
into the third round

27:20.639 --> 27:23.100
of this competition.
Now, when you came here,

27:23.100 --> 27:25.644
we had you make signature
blades in your signature style.

27:25.644 --> 27:28.021
That's not gonna happen
at your home forges.

27:28.021 --> 27:30.691
Instead you'll be making
one of these...

27:30.691 --> 27:33.235
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:33.235 --> 27:34.987
Genghis Khan's sword.

27:34.987 --> 27:37.322
‐ Sweet.

27:37.322 --> 27:39.700
<i>‐ One of the most notorious</i>
<i>rulers in history,</i>

27:39.700 --> 27:41.660
<i>Genghis Khan</i>
<i>and his Mongolian army</i>

27:41.660 --> 27:43.620
<i>conquered the Asian continent</i>
<i>through terrifying</i>

27:43.620 --> 27:46.540
<i>land seizures</i>
<i>throughout the 13th century.</i>

27:46.540 --> 27:48.876
<i>Khan and his troops</i>
<i>used the slightly curved sword</i>

27:48.876 --> 27:51.378
<i>to inflict deep and lethal</i>
<i>attacks during horse raids,</i>

27:51.378 --> 27:54.548
<i>killing tens of millions</i>
<i>of people in their path.</i>

27:54.548 --> 27:55.966
<i>This brutal single‐edged blade</i>

27:55.966 --> 27:57.676
<i>was lightweight for sustained</i>
<i>mounted combat</i>

27:57.676 --> 28:00.971
<i>while the razor‐sharp edge</i>
<i>easily decapitated prisoners,</i>

28:00.971 --> 28:04.641
<i>which was often the tactic used</i>
<i>when seizing new territory.</i>

28:04.641 --> 28:06.685
<i>Having established</i>
<i>the Mongol Empire,</i>

28:06.685 --> 28:09.187
<i>one of the largest land</i>
<i>empires to date,</i>

28:09.187 --> 28:12.024
<i>Genghis Khan remains one of</i>
<i>the most prolific rulers</i>

28:12.024 --> 28:13.734
<i>in history.</i>

28:13.734 --> 28:17.237
The length of the blade must be
between 28 and 30 inches.

28:17.237 --> 28:19.448
You must have a fuller
on each side of the blade.

28:19.448 --> 28:21.575
This must be
a slightly curved blade.

28:21.575 --> 28:23.744
You must also have
a downswept handle,

28:23.744 --> 28:28.582
an octagon guard, a butt cap,
and a tassel ring.

28:28.582 --> 28:31.376
‐ I have not normally
made swords.

28:31.376 --> 28:35.631
<i>I usually make kitchen cutlery,</i>
<i>but I can do this.</i>

28:35.631 --> 28:38.342
‐ At the end of your four days,
you'll return and present

28:38.342 --> 28:40.427
your swords
to our panel of expert judges.

28:40.427 --> 28:41.929
After they've thoroughly
tested them,

28:41.929 --> 28:44.556
they'll call one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

28:44.556 --> 28:47.935
and you'll walk out of here
with a check for $10,000.

28:47.935 --> 28:50.145
Good luck.
We'll see you in four days.

28:50.145 --> 28:51.396
‐ Bring your A game.

28:51.396 --> 28:52.940
‐ I'll bring my A‐plus game.

28:52.940 --> 28:55.567
[laughter]

28:55.567 --> 28:58.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:58.528 --> 29:00.864
<i>‐ It's day one, and I'm ready</i>

29:00.864 --> 29:04.409
to get going
on this Genghis Khan sword.

29:04.409 --> 29:06.370
It's starting with a bang,
baby.

29:06.370 --> 29:08.413
<i>I'm gonna do some Damascus.</i>

29:08.413 --> 29:09.957
<i>We'll see how it goes.</i>

29:09.957 --> 29:12.459
I could just use a mono steel,
already be on my way,

29:12.459 --> 29:14.670
<i>but I want to make it</i>
<i>a little more elaborate.</i>

29:14.670 --> 29:17.089
<i>I know my competitor's</i>
<i>gonna be tough.</i>

29:17.089 --> 29:19.049
<i>I already told him</i>
<i>to bring his A game,</i>

29:19.049 --> 29:20.759
so I need to bring mine.

29:20.759 --> 29:23.804
<i>First thing I gotta do today</i>
<i>is take these pieces of steel,</i>

29:23.804 --> 29:25.931
<i>bringing it up to forge heat</i>
<i>squishing it,</i>

29:25.931 --> 29:29.935
<i>drawing it out, wire brush,</i>
<i>clean it, put some flux on it,</i>

29:29.935 --> 29:31.561
<i>put it back in the forge,</i>
<i>heat it up,</i>

29:31.561 --> 29:35.691
so it's a lot of heat,
beat, and repeat.

29:35.691 --> 29:37.150
Sounds pretty solid.

29:37.150 --> 29:38.694
<i>I feel good about my billet.</i>

29:38.694 --> 29:40.904
<i>I'm starting</i>
<i>to draw it out now.</i>

29:40.904 --> 29:44.491
It's been a pretty hard day,
and I'm gonna eat and sleep.

29:44.491 --> 29:48.954
Tomorrow we'll do it again,
eat, sleep, beat, and repeat.

29:48.954 --> 29:51.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:51.915 --> 29:53.417
<i>‐ I'm back in Austin, Texas,</i>

29:53.417 --> 29:57.295
and I have to make
Genghis Khan's sword.

29:57.295 --> 29:59.047
Let's get to work.

29:59.047 --> 30:01.091
<i>I was considering</i>
<i>a Damascus bill,</i>

30:01.091 --> 30:02.467
but I think it's a risk.

30:02.467 --> 30:06.638
You're asking for potential
delams and weak points,

30:06.638 --> 30:09.516
<i>so I'm thinking</i>
<i>a strong mono steel here.</i>

30:09.516 --> 30:11.977
I'm gonna go function,
function, function.

30:11.977 --> 30:13.937
I think this is gonna be
a challenge no matter what,

30:13.937 --> 30:15.689
<i>just sheer length of‐‐you know,</i>

30:15.689 --> 30:18.025
<i>the longer it is, it's harder</i>
<i>to keep these things straight.</i>

30:18.025 --> 30:22.487
You're asking for warps
and other weirdness to go on.

30:22.487 --> 30:24.489
I'm hoping to get
the whole fuller in today

30:24.489 --> 30:27.159
<i>and the tang shaped out.</i>

30:27.159 --> 30:30.037
Pretty happy with it
how it's going so far.

30:30.037 --> 30:34.166
So basically, my sword
is ready to quench now.

30:34.166 --> 30:35.333
I pull it out.

30:35.333 --> 30:39.212
Wow, it's pretty straight,
and it's hard.

30:39.212 --> 30:40.881
This is a huge relief.

30:40.881 --> 30:42.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:42.632 --> 30:44.134
<i>‐ So this is day two.</i>

30:44.134 --> 30:46.094
It seems like day ten
or something.

30:46.094 --> 30:48.680
<i>It's brutal.</i>
<i>I'm forging along.</i>

30:48.680 --> 30:50.849
<i>It's starting</i>
<i>to stretch out nicely.</i>

30:50.849 --> 30:52.976
<i>I want to leave it</i>
<i>a little bit thick</i>

30:52.976 --> 30:55.187
to avoid a big...
[whooshes]

30:55.187 --> 30:58.231
Should be able
to get into some heat‐treat.

30:58.231 --> 31:00.776
<i>I really want to get this done</i>
<i>right the first time.</i>

31:00.776 --> 31:03.028
<i>I don't want something</i>
<i>to go wrong.</i>

31:03.028 --> 31:04.446
<i>I pull it out.</i>

31:04.446 --> 31:07.199
Not bad.
Not like a pool stick, but..

31:07.199 --> 31:09.034
It's got a little
whoop‐de‐doo in,

31:09.034 --> 31:11.369
<i>but I've got a lot of meat</i>
<i>on the blade</i>

31:11.369 --> 31:12.579
to straighten that out.

31:12.579 --> 31:15.791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:15.791 --> 31:17.459
<i>‐ I'm a little tired,</i>
<i>but nothing</i>

31:17.459 --> 31:19.419
some good coffee
won't cure.

31:19.419 --> 31:22.255
I got an octagonal guard
knocked out,

31:22.255 --> 31:24.716
and I'm gonna make some epoxy
and set some pins,

31:24.716 --> 31:28.428
and then we'll start thinking
about our butt cap.

31:28.428 --> 31:33.016
My plan is to put this butt
guard on and use the press

31:33.016 --> 31:36.228
<i>just real gently to conform</i>
<i>the metal over the groove</i>

31:36.228 --> 31:38.271
and lock it into place,

31:38.271 --> 31:41.108
so it's got this
physical connection.

31:41.108 --> 31:42.526
<i>I go to the press.</i>

31:42.526 --> 31:45.987
<i>It feels like it should</i>
<i>just press into place,</i>

31:45.987 --> 31:49.282
and it immediately goes south.

31:49.282 --> 31:51.284
Ah, crap.

31:51.284 --> 31:53.328
I break my freaking handle.

31:55.831 --> 31:58.250
‐ It looks like I popped it
open here.
It looks like
I popped it op

31:58.250 --> 31:59.668
I notice the handle's
screwed up,

31:59.668 --> 32:02.420
<i>so I gotta pry it off</i>
<i>and clean everything up</i>

32:02.420 --> 32:05.132
and re‐epoxy,
re‐pin everything.

32:05.132 --> 32:06.508
Round two.

32:06.508 --> 32:08.677
<i>I also have to fix the butt cap</i>

32:08.677 --> 32:13.098
that I messed up trying
to press it into the tang.

32:13.098 --> 32:14.599
<i>I have to change my game plan</i>

32:14.599 --> 32:16.935
<i>and attach the butt plate</i>
<i>by epoxy.</i>

32:16.935 --> 32:20.105
<i>I do feel like I'll be able to</i>
<i>get a handle on the situation.</i>

32:20.105 --> 32:21.773
<i>[laughs]</i>

32:21.773 --> 32:24.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:24.276 --> 32:26.945
‐ Trying to figure out
the handle design.

32:26.945 --> 32:29.406
<i>The finishing of the weapon,</i>
<i>I feel,</i>

32:29.406 --> 32:31.366
is the most time‐consuming.

32:31.366 --> 32:32.951
This is tedious.

32:32.951 --> 32:35.162
<i>So I got this curved tang</i>
<i>to deal with,</i>

32:35.162 --> 32:37.622
<i>so I decide</i>
<i>to cut the pieces up.</i>

32:37.622 --> 32:38.957
♪ ♪

32:38.957 --> 32:41.418
<i>My idea is to have</i>
<i>the tang sticking out,</i>

32:41.418 --> 32:43.128
<i>'cause I have to put</i>
<i>this little hole in there</i>

32:43.128 --> 32:45.463
for a little...
[whistling]

32:45.463 --> 32:46.631
Little tassel.

32:46.631 --> 32:49.301
<i>Put the handle together,</i>
<i>doing a dry fit.</i>

32:49.301 --> 32:51.928
Uh‐oh.
See my angle's way off.

32:51.928 --> 32:53.471
Hmm.

32:53.471 --> 32:55.974
I'm gonna go bend
this tang just a hair.

32:55.974 --> 32:58.476
It's gonna be real close.

32:58.476 --> 33:00.979
<i>I really thought I'd be further</i>
<i>along, like,</i>

33:00.979 --> 33:03.148
<i>pretty much done right now,</i>

33:03.148 --> 33:06.610
but I think I'm set up good
for tomorrow to finish.

33:06.610 --> 33:08.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:08.403 --> 33:09.863
<i>‐ It's the last day.</i>

33:09.863 --> 33:13.533
I have a sword, so now
it's sharpen, sharpen, sharpen.

33:13.533 --> 33:15.285
<i>I'm going for</i>
<i>a very sharp edge,</i>

33:15.285 --> 33:18.121
<i>and that's a bit</i>
<i>of a calculated risk,</i>

33:18.121 --> 33:19.831
so it will certainly help
in a cut

33:19.831 --> 33:23.293
and potentially KEAL test,
but if the strength test

33:23.293 --> 33:26.129
<i>is bashing against bones</i>
<i>or something,</i>

33:26.129 --> 33:29.758
<i>then this could be</i>
<i>a detractor for me.</i>

33:29.758 --> 33:32.177
I believe my sword
is a lot like Genghis Khan,

33:32.177 --> 33:35.430
<i>actually, sharp</i>
<i>and really frickin' brutal.</i>

33:35.430 --> 33:37.599
<i>And I think there's only</i>
<i>one thing left to do.</i>

33:37.599 --> 33:39.643
We gotta give this
some sort of test.

33:39.643 --> 33:44.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:44.522 --> 33:47.525
Whew.
Okay. That was kinda cool.

33:47.525 --> 33:54.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:54.032 --> 33:55.700
‐ Peter, Everett, welcome back
to The Forge.

33:55.700 --> 33:57.702
You had four days at your home
forges to work

33:57.702 --> 34:00.872
on your version
of Genghis Khan's sword.

34:00.872 --> 34:02.374
Peter, tell us
about your blade.

34:02.374 --> 34:04.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:04.167 --> 34:05.961
<i>‐ My blade's 41 layers.</i>

34:05.961 --> 34:08.588
<i>The handle is a tree</i>
<i>I cut down.</i>

34:08.588 --> 34:12.133
<i>The brass is from</i>
<i>an elevator handrail.</i>

34:12.133 --> 34:13.760
‐ All right, all right.
Everett,

34:13.760 --> 34:17.222
how much detail did you
put into your blade?

34:17.222 --> 34:21.726
<i>‐ Uh, mine is made out</i>
<i>of 80CrV2 with a brass guard</i>

34:21.726 --> 34:25.021
<i>and butt plate</i>
<i>and African rosewood.</i>

34:25.021 --> 34:27.065
‐ All right, gentlemen,
to determine which one of you

34:27.065 --> 34:29.651
is our next "Forged in Fire"
champion, your weapons will now

34:29.651 --> 34:31.236
be put through
a series of three tests.

34:31.236 --> 34:33.905
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

34:33.905 --> 34:35.740
and up first, a KEAL test.

34:35.740 --> 34:38.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:38.326 --> 34:42.163
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
welcome to the KEAL test.

34:42.163 --> 34:45.166
To find out what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

34:45.166 --> 34:47.836
I will take your sword
and deliver some killing blows

34:47.836 --> 34:48.962
to this ballistics dummy.

34:48.962 --> 34:50.171
Peter, you're up first.
You ready?

34:50.171 --> 34:51.923
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

34:51.923 --> 34:53.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:53.341 --> 34:56.052
‐ My fear is my blade breaking.

34:56.052 --> 34:58.847
<i>The ballistics dummy</i>
<i>looks soft on the outside,</i>

34:58.847 --> 35:02.392
<i>but there's bone and all kinds</i>
<i>of hard material in there.</i>

35:02.392 --> 35:09.357
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.540 --> 35:27.959
[chuckling]

35:27.959 --> 35:32.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.130 --> 35:35.967
‐ All right, Peter, first up,
your edge is sharp.

35:35.967 --> 35:37.636
The balance feels good,

35:37.636 --> 35:41.348
but it did take
quite a pronounced bend,

35:41.348 --> 35:44.601
but the more important thing
is, it will KEAL.

35:44.601 --> 35:46.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:46.770 --> 35:47.854
I timed that perfectly.

35:47.854 --> 35:49.147
‐ [laughs]

35:49.147 --> 35:51.358
‐ All right, Doc Everett,
are you ready, sir?

35:51.358 --> 35:52.984
‐ Let's do some surgery.

35:52.984 --> 35:59.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:19.260 --> 36:21.137
‐ Yikes.
‐ [scoffs]

36:21.137 --> 36:24.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:24.140 --> 36:27.477
‐ All right, Everett,
your edge is very sharp.

36:27.477 --> 36:28.770
It slashes nicely.

36:28.770 --> 36:32.023
Your tip punctures easily,
cuts on the way out.

36:32.023 --> 36:35.235
With all these cuts,
it will KEAL.

36:35.235 --> 36:38.029
‐ [laughs]

36:38.029 --> 36:40.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:40.615 --> 36:42.701
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test.

36:42.701 --> 36:44.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:44.035 --> 36:45.120
Now, to test the strength

36:45.120 --> 36:47.122
and overall construction
of your blades,

36:47.122 --> 36:50.458
I'll be attacking
our armored targets over here.

36:50.458 --> 36:52.377
Peter, you're up first.
Are you ready?

36:52.377 --> 36:54.379
‐ Let her rip, tater chip.

36:57.632 --> 36:59.008
<i>‐ Dave's got my blade,</i>

36:59.008 --> 37:02.095
and I'm just kind of
coming out of my skin.

37:02.095 --> 37:04.514
<i>With this warp,</i>
<i>I'm scared it's gonna break.</i>

37:04.514 --> 37:11.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:19.696 --> 37:22.157
‐ All right, Peter, um,

37:22.157 --> 37:24.075
I'm gonna start
with your handle.

37:24.075 --> 37:25.744
I find it really comfortable,

37:25.744 --> 37:27.746
the way it flares
towards the tip.

37:27.746 --> 37:30.081
Works pretty good for my hand,
and I love what you did

37:30.081 --> 37:32.250
with this kind of
low‐layer‐count Damascus.

37:32.250 --> 37:37.255
It's very dramatic,
but we've got some

37:37.255 --> 37:39.841
very deep rolls on this edge.

37:39.841 --> 37:41.760
[sword dinging]
There you go.

37:41.760 --> 37:43.178
You hear it.

37:43.178 --> 37:45.180
Those chips, that's an issue,

37:45.180 --> 37:49.309
but all in all,
you did a good job.

37:49.309 --> 37:51.019
All right, Everett, you ready?

37:51.019 --> 37:53.104
‐ I am.
‐ Okay.

37:53.104 --> 37:56.149
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:56.149 --> 37:58.026
<i>‐ I'm a little worried</i>
<i>of this one,</i>

37:58.026 --> 38:01.946
'cause I have a very fine edge,
and anytime you're bashing

38:01.946 --> 38:04.115
<i>a really fine edge</i>
<i>into the hard surface,</i>

38:04.115 --> 38:07.410
<i>you're gonna have a chance</i>
<i>of chipping or losing your edge</i>

38:07.410 --> 38:08.745
or breaking, even.

38:08.745 --> 38:15.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.798 --> 38:21.257
‐ Eh, piece of armor.

38:21.257 --> 38:27.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:27.931 --> 38:29.641
‐ Nice.

38:29.641 --> 38:31.810
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:31.810 --> 38:35.313
‐ All right, Everett,
your blade, still spot‐on.

38:35.313 --> 38:39.651
What I really like is the fact
that‐‐that that blade

38:39.651 --> 38:43.822
is at its widest point
maybe 3/16 of an inch.

38:43.822 --> 38:46.991
You don't need weight and mass
for strength

38:46.991 --> 38:48.993
in a properly tempered blade.
That's really good.

38:48.993 --> 38:52.080
You've got a section of blade
here that's not quite as sharp

38:52.080 --> 38:53.832
as it was right there.

38:53.832 --> 38:56.376
All in all,
I think you did a great job.

38:56.376 --> 38:58.795
‐ Awesome.

38:58.795 --> 39:01.297
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:01.297 --> 39:04.801
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
this is the war banner slice.

39:04.801 --> 39:06.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:06.344 --> 39:08.179
To test the sharpness
of your blade,

39:08.179 --> 39:11.224
I will take your weapon and
slash across these war banners.

39:11.224 --> 39:12.517
Peter, you're up first.
You ready?

39:12.517 --> 39:14.185
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

39:14.185 --> 39:21.192
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:40.712 --> 39:43.756
So where your edge has a chip,

39:43.756 --> 39:46.384
you can see it catches
and rips through the banner.

39:46.384 --> 39:48.803
Where it's not, it cuts nicely.

39:48.803 --> 39:52.473
Overall, sir, it will cut.

39:52.473 --> 39:54.183
All right, Everett,
it's your turn. You ready, sir?

39:54.183 --> 39:56.436
‐ I think this beats the hell
out of peer review.

39:56.436 --> 39:57.520
‐ All right, let's find out.

39:57.520 --> 39:59.230
‐ [chuckling]

39:59.230 --> 40:06.237
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:20.501 --> 40:24.464
Okay, Everett, your edge
here does cut. It's sharp.

40:24.464 --> 40:26.174
It cuts in some of the areas.

40:26.174 --> 40:30.929
On some parts of it, it ripped,
but overall, sir, it will cut.

40:30.929 --> 40:32.889
‐ Awesome.

40:32.889 --> 40:36.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:36.017 --> 40:37.268
‐ All right, gentlemen,
based on what we've seen

40:37.268 --> 40:38.311
in the weapons tests,

40:38.311 --> 40:40.188
the judges have made
their final decision

40:40.188 --> 40:42.899
about which of you is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:42.899 --> 40:46.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:46.277 --> 40:50.448
Peter, your sword took the most
damage in our strength test.

40:50.448 --> 40:52.951
<i>You had a rolled edge,</i>
<i>and your blade bent.</i>

40:52.951 --> 40:54.285
For that reason,

40:54.285 --> 40:56.120
I have to dismiss you
from The Forge.

40:56.120 --> 40:58.873
Come on forward.

40:58.873 --> 41:00.041
‐ I feel a little sad.
Thank you.

41:00.041 --> 41:01.918
But it's been
an awesome experience.

41:01.918 --> 41:03.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:03.836 --> 41:05.797
<i>This loss</i>
<i>is not gonna deter me.</i>

41:05.797 --> 41:08.549
It's gonna just
make me stronger.

41:08.549 --> 41:11.844
<i>I may not be</i>
<i>the "Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

41:11.844 --> 41:14.430
but I still think
I'm a badass smith.

41:14.430 --> 41:17.809
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:17.809 --> 41:19.352
‐ Well, Everett,
your blade is comfortable,

41:19.352 --> 41:20.895
well‐balanced,
strong, and deadly,

41:20.895 --> 41:22.814
and that makes you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

41:22.814 --> 41:25.483
and that's a title that comes
with a check for 10 grand.

41:25.483 --> 41:27.652
Good job. Come on forward
and shake our hands, man.

41:27.652 --> 41:28.987
‐ [laughs]

41:28.987 --> 41:30.655
This experience
was really fun.

41:30.655 --> 41:33.074
It was really tough
in a lot of places,

41:33.074 --> 41:36.119
and it's been a hell of a ride.

41:36.119 --> 41:41.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>
